6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges calculate funding rates hourly using similar mark-to-index methodologies. dYdX V4 operates on its dedicated Cosmos appchain with sovereign validators determining rates through on-chain consensus. Paradex leverages StarkNet's validity proofs for rate calculations and settlements. While both use 1-hour intervals, dYdX benefits from higher liquidity leading to more stable rates, whereas Paradex's institutional focus may create different rate patterns during low retail activity periods."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"dYdX currently provides more consistent funding rate opportunities due to higher trading volumes and established market making. Paradex is too early-stage for reliable rate arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"How do settlement mechanisms differ between these DEXs?","answer":"dYdX V4 operates on its own Cosmos appchain with native settlement, while Paradex uses StarkNet validity proofs. Both offer self-custody but dYdX has faster finality."},{"question":"Are funding intervals the same on both platforms?","answer":"Yes, both exchanges use 1-hour funding intervals. However, dYdX's higher liquidity typically results in more predictable rate movements compared to Paradex's volatile early-stage rates."},{"question":"Which platform is better for institutional funding strategies?","answer":"Paradex targets institutional users with portfolio margin and Jump Trading infrastructure, but dYdX's proven volume and stability make it more suitable for serious funding rate arbitrage operations currently."}]}]
